Germany: a costly budget fetish
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is under fierce attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
It is indeed Germany that insisted that this principle be incorporated into the criteria outlined in the Maastricht Treaty, which set the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone implied a political regime change.
Thus, the independence of the Banque de France was one of the strongest arguments of the anti-euro campaign during the ratification referendum of the Maastricht Treaty in 1992.
In today's Germany, it has become commonplace, one might say, to exert pressure on the central bank.
Since a few months, even the Minister of Finance, Wolfgang Schaüble, has regularly commented on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
The interventions of Schaüble target the very core of what constitutes the central bank's independence.
If he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (this "price norm," in the old jargon of the Bundesbank), he nonetheless provides his advice on the tools the ECB should use and on how it should handle them to achieve such an aim.
There are precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then Germany's Finance Minister, gave his advice to the first President of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's goal was, in the end, to create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with his typically Dutch laconicism, replied that it was nothing unusual for a politician to express his opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unheard of). "Yet – he added – it would be entirely abnormal to take account of [his] suggestions."
Schaüble's interventions strike at the very heart of what constitutes the central bank's independence.
The respect for the independence of monetary policy has long been a central element of Germany's Stabilitätskultur ("stability culture").
The foundational act that established the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to Chancellor Konrad Adenauer's urging in 1956, who wanted it to contain the rise in interest rates.
At that time, France did not see things the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was about to create the Fifth Republic, with a Bank of France that reported to the Finance Minister.
But it was a different time.
As a result of the various crises that have shaken theEMU, monetary policy is increasingly replacing fiscal policy.
Would the old dogma have become obsolete?
The Europe remains very vulnerable; the average citizen of the EMU has already lost ten years, and what is even more alarming, we are close to a critical situation.
The United States, however, do better.
Despite facing a difficult political deadlock, they managed to address the macroeconomic issue (the weakness of aggregate demand) they were facing by implementing expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States have also managed their banking problems better, which were initially far more severe than in Europe.
There is obviously a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.
The more robust an economy is, the more profitable its banks are and the more capable they are of fulfilling their function: financing the economy.
But the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the good advice of a finance minister than by the lack of support from the populations.
And indeed, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the indelible support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voices are being heard, notably in Germany, calling for it to be subjected to greater pressure.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's autonomy lies in the unbearable burden that weighs on its shoulders.
The less fiscal policy is called upon to stabilize production, the more central banks are effectively forced to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let things take their course, allowing the economy to sink into stagnation, or worse).
The political result of this chain of events is a very clear regression toward nationalism, both from the right and the left, in all the countries of the EMU, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And there too, Germany leads the dance, driven by its obsession with the schwarze Null and budget balance, against all winds and tides.
In Germany, deficits are viewed unfavorably not only from an arithmetic but also a moral standpoint, even though this defies economic common sense and resembles clientelism.
At the end of the 19th century, leading German public finance specialists, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, formulated a "golden rule" according to which current expenditures should, on average, be financed by current revenues.
Public spending, and the resources it requires, are justified by their utility.
This amounts to saying that investments aimed at improving productivity – equipment spending – can be financed with debt, whose service is ensured by the growth of incomes and the base of associated revenues.
This traditional approach was institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and investment expenditures, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
It is crucial, because in Germany, about 50% of public sector investment spending is managed at this level (a proportion that has been declining, since the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with support for the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (Mittelstand).
But compared to the beginning of the 1990s and at constant prices, investment spending has decreased by about 15%.
More than a decade has passed, and they have been insufficient to maintain the capital stock.
If this is not how one prepares for the future, it is how one undermines productivity and prosperity.
In short, the schwarze Null goes against the intended goal.
The aging infrastructure (certainly not as severe as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
In addition, the fiscal frugality of German leaders spills over beyond Germany's borders, and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which lacks exchange rates to accommodate national particularities.
Of course, the European monetary union is imperfect.
But to make the only institution capable of "doing what it takes" to bring the EMU back on track into a scapegoat is a very bad idea.
Let the states use, where it exists, the budgetary space they have to relieve pressure on the ECB would be a far better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, enjoys a certain degree of maneuvering room in this regard.
